  "prompt": "How is RMM calculated in chemistry?",
  "response": "In chemistry, RMM stands for **Relative Molecular Mass**, which is the sum of the **atomic masses** of all the atoms in a molecule. It is calculated by:\n\n1. Identifying the chemical formula of the molecule.\n2. Determining the **atomic mass** of each element in the molecule (from the periodic table).\n3. Multiplying each atomic mass by the number of atoms of that element in the molecule.\n4. Adding up the results to get the RMM.\n\nFor example, to calculate the RMM of water (H\u2082O):\n- Atomic mass of hydrogen (H) = 1 (approximately).\n- Atomic mass of oxygen (O) = 16.\n- Number of H atoms = 2, number of O atoms = 1.\n\nRMM = (2 \u00d7 1) + (1 \u00d7 16) = 2 + 16 = **18**.\n\nNote: RMM is dimensionless (no units) because it is a relative value based on the atomic mass units (u).",
